1.Esoph Analysis

With this analysis, which factors affect (o)esophageal cancer are examined. esoph dataset provides some information about these factors such as alcohol consumption, age or tobacco consumption.

Let’s have a look at the data.

The dataset include the number of cancer cases. In order to have an insight, observing the ncases column by visualizing is beneficial.

esoph%>%ggplot(aes(x=ncases))+
  geom_histogram(fill="purple",binwidth=0.8,color="blue")

After some of the column names are arranged, I assigned numbers to the character columns Age,alcohol and tobaccop by using the function as.numeric(). In this way, a correlation among these factors can be shown.

For instance, age_rank and ncases are positively correlated which makes sense. Although, it is not a strong analysis, it provides an insight.

colnames(esoph)[1]  <- "Age"
colnames(esoph)[2]  <- "alcohol"
colnames(esoph)[3]  <- "tobacco"


esoph["alcohol_rank"]<-as.numeric(esoph$alcohol)
esoph["tobacco_rank"]<-as.numeric(esoph$tobacco)
esoph["age_rank"]<-as.numeric(esoph$Age)
correlation<-cor(esoph[,4:8])

By grouping the data with respect to Age, a percentage of cancer cases is calculated. Thus, the percentage of cases can be seen clearly according to the age groups.

age<-esoph%>%group_by(Age)%>%summarise(total_cases=sum(ncases), total_controls=sum(ncontrols),age_perc=100*(total_cases/total_controls))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
age%>%ggplot(aes(x=Age,y=age_perc,fill=Age))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  labs(x="Age",y="Case Percentage")+
  scale_fill_manual(name="legend", values = c("25-34" = "dark green", "35-44" ="orange", "45-54" = "light blue","55-64" = "red","65-74"="purple","75+"="yellow"))

Like the previous analysis, by grouping the data with respect to alcohol, a percentage of cancer cases is calculated. Thus, the percentage of cases can be seen clearly according to the alcohol consumption groups.

alcohol<-esoph%>%group_by(alcohol)%>%summarise(total_cases=sum(ncases), total_controls=sum(ncontrols),alcohol_perc=100*(total_cases/total_controls))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
alcohol%>%ggplot(aes(x=alcohol,y=alcohol_perc,fill=alcohol))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  scale_fill_manual(name="legend", values = c("0-39g/day" = "dark green", "40-79" ="orange","80-119"="purple","120+"="dark red"))

Again by grouping the data with respect to tobacco, a percentage of cancer cases is calculated. Thus, the percentage of cases can be seen clearly according to the tobacco consumption groups.

tobacco<-esoph%>%group_by(tobacco)%>%summarise(total_cases=sum(ncases), total_controls=sum(ncontrols),tobacco_perc=100*(total_cases/total_controls))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
tobacco%>%ggplot(aes(x=tobacco,y=tobacco_perc,fill=tobacco))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  scale_fill_manual(name="legend", values = c("0-9g/day" = "black", "10-19" = "orange", "20-29" = "blue","30+" = "red"))

Now, the dual series of analysis are shown in the graphs below.

Faceting is used to observe the effects of both tobacco consumption and age groups. More concrete analysis than the previous ones is shown here.

age_tobacco<-esoph %>%group_by(Age,tobacco) %>%
  summarise(total_cases = sum(ncases), total_controls = sum(ncontrols),perc=total_cases/total_controls)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Age' (override with `.groups` argument)
age_tobacco%>%ggplot(aes(x=tobacco,y=perc,fill=Age))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  facet_wrap(~Age)

Again, faceting is used to observe the effects of both alcohol consumption and age groups.

age_alcohol<-esoph %>%group_by(Age,alcohol) %>%
  summarise(total_cases = sum(ncases), total_controls = sum(ncontrols),perc=total_cases/total_controls)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Age' (override with `.groups` argument)
age_alcohol%>%ggplot(aes(x=alcohol,y=perc,fill=Age))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity")+
  facet_wrap(~Age)

The final plot related to esoph dataset indicates that the mean of ncontrols and ncases together. Basically, it can be stated that the correlation between the number of controls and cases is positive.

p<-esoph%>%group_by(Age)%>%summarise(mean_case=mean(ncases),mean_controls=mean(ncontrols))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
p%>%ggplot() +
  labs(x="Age", y= "Cases and Controls")+
  geom_point(aes(x=Age, y=mean_controls,color="mean_controls"))+
  geom_point(aes(x=Age, y=mean_case,color="mean_case"))

1.1 Logistic Regression Model of the esoph DataSet

In this analysis, the model demonstrates the variables which affect the percentage of canser cases. Since the median value, -0.1171, is close to zero, the model is pretty accurate. Moreover, the result of summary() function indicates that the most significant determinants, which are mainly age and alcohol consumption.

esoph<-esoph%>%mutate(Percentage=ncases/ncontrols)
model<-glm(Percentage ~ Age + alcohol + tobacco,data = esoph, family = quasibinomial)
summary(model)

2.Young People Survey Analysis

In this part of the assignment, the Young People Survey’s Hobbies & Interests category answers are examined. In order to conduct this analysis, PCA model and Multidimensional Scaling Methods are used.

data<-read.csv("C:/Users/tumay/Desktop/Young_People_Survey.csv")

The plot method returns a plot of the variances (y-axis) associated with the components (x-axis).In this case, it can be seen that the first 15 responses explain 60% of the variability of the data.

ggplot(data=data.frame(PC=1:length(data_pca$sdev),var_exp=cumsum(data_pca$sdev^2/sum(data_pca$sdev^2))),
       aes(x=PC,y=var_exp)) + geom_line(color="pink",size=1) + geom_point(color="orange") + scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent,breaks=seq(0,1,length.out=11)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0,135,by=5))

2.2 Multidimensional Scaling

In this part, Multidimensional Scaling method is conducted on the data. This method shows the level of similarity among the selected components.

set.seed(250)

yr_dist<- 1 - cor(filtered_data)
yr_mds <- cmdscale(yr_dist,k=2)
colnames(yr_mds) <- c("x","y")
print(yr_mds)
